  1: {
    emailType: 'newsletter_jan',
    subject_a: 'Winter survival guide for your Madison yard',
    subject_b: '{{first_name}}, 3 things killing your yard right now (and how to stop them)',
    preview_text: 'Salt damage, frozen grass, ice dams \u2014 here\'s how to protect your yard this winter.',
    headline: 'The Yard Report: Winter Survival Guide',
    intro_text: 'Happy New Year, {{first_name}}! January in Madison means sub-zero temps, heavy snow, and hidden threats to your yard. Most homeowners don\'t think about their lawn in winter \u2014 but what you do (and don\'t do) right now determines how your yard looks in April. Here are three things to watch for this month.',
    content_html: '<h3>1. Protect Your Evergreens from Road Salt Spray</h3><p>If you have evergreens, arborvitae, or boxwoods within 30 feet of a road or driveway, they\'re getting hit with salt spray every time a plow or car drives by. Salt pulls moisture out of needles and leaves, causing brown, dead patches that don\'t recover. <strong>The fix:</strong> Rinse exposed evergreens with plain water during any mid-winter thaw (when temps hit 35\u00b0F+). Even one good rinse can prevent major damage. If you haven\'t already, consider burlap screens for your most exposed shrubs.</p><h3>2. Stop Walking on Frozen Grass</h3><p>We get it \u2014 shortcuts across the lawn save 30 seconds. But frozen grass blades are brittle. When you walk on them, the blades snap at the crown, creating dead footpaths that show up as brown streaks in spring. <strong>The rule:</strong> If there\'s frost on the grass, stay on the sidewalk. This goes for pets too \u2014 try to keep the dog\'s path to a consistent trail rather than letting them roam the entire yard.</p><h3>3. Check Your Gutters for Ice Dams</h3><p>Look up at your roofline after a heavy snow. See thick ridges of ice along the edge? That\'s an ice dam, and it means water is backing up under your shingles. Beyond roof damage, ice dams cause massive icicles that can rip gutters right off the fascia. <strong>What to do:</strong> If you see ice dam formation, don\'t hack at it with a hammer (you\'ll damage the gutters). Use a roof rake to clear snow from the first 3-4 feet of your roof edge, or call a professional. And if your gutters need attention this spring, that\'s exactly what we\'re here for.</p>',
