    preview_text: 'Soil pH, tool prep, and the spring tasks you should schedule right now.',
    headline: 'The Yard Report: Spring Is Closer Than You Think',
    intro_text: 'Hey {{first_name}} \u2014 February feels like the dead of winter, but experienced Madison gardeners know: this is planning season. The homeowners who have the best-looking yards in May are the ones who start prepping in February. Here\'s your checklist.',
    content_html: '<h3>1. Plan Your Spring Yard Tasks Now</h3><p>Don\'t wait for the snow to melt to figure out what needs doing. Walk your property on the next mild day and take stock: <strong>Are there areas where the lawn looks thin?</strong> Those need overseeding in April. <strong>Did any bushes get damaged by ice?</strong> Flag them for trimming. <strong>Are your garden beds overgrown from last fall?</strong> That\'s a spring cleanup priority. Write it all down now so you\'re not scrambling in April when every lawn care company in Madison is booked solid.</p><h3>2. Test Your Soil pH</h3><p>Wisconsin soil tends to run slightly acidic, especially in areas with lots of oak trees. You can grab a soil test kit from the Dane County UW-Extension office for about $20 \u2014 it\'s the single best investment you can make for your lawn. <strong>Why it matters:</strong> If your soil pH is off, fertilizer literally doesn\'t work. Grass can\'t absorb nutrients outside the 6.0-7.0 range. A soil test tells you exactly what amendments to apply, so you\'re not throwing money at products that won\'t help.</p><h3>3. Prep Your Tools (or Better Yet, Let Us Handle It)</h3><p>If you do any DIY yard work, February is the month to sharpen mower blades, change the oil, replace spark plugs, and clean out the garage. Dull mower blades tear grass instead of cutting it, which stresses the lawn and invites disease. <strong>Pro tip:</strong> A sharp blade makes a clean cut that heals fast. A dull blade leaves ragged edges that turn brown.</p>',
