  3: {
    emailType: 'newsletter_mar',
    subject_a: 'Spring awakening \u2014 when to start what in your Madison yard',
    subject_b: '{{first_name}}, the timing on these 3 spring tasks is everything',
    preview_text: 'First raking, first mow, early weed prevention \u2014 get the timing right and your lawn wins.',
    headline: 'The Yard Report: Spring Awakening',
    intro_text: 'It\'s March, {{first_name}} \u2014 and in Madison, that means anything from 55\u00b0F and sunny to 8 inches of wet snow. But the ground is starting to thaw, and your yard is waking up whether you\'re ready or not. Here\'s how to make the most of it.',
    content_html: '<h3>1. When to Start Raking (Hint: Not Yet)</h3><p>We know the urge to get out there on the first warm day. But raking too early does more harm than good. <strong>Wait until the ground is firm and the grass is no longer saturated.</strong> Walking on soggy soil compacts it, which suffocates roots and creates drainage problems all season. In the Madison area, that usually means mid-to-late March depending on the year. A good test: if your footprints leave impressions in the lawn, it\'s too wet. Wait a few more days.</p><h3>2. First Mow Timing for Wisconsin</h3><p>Your first mow should happen when the grass has actively started growing \u2014 typically when it reaches 3.5-4 inches. In south-central Wisconsin, that\'s usually late March to mid-April depending on sun exposure and soil temperature. <strong>Set your mower to 3 inches for the first cut.</strong></p><h3>3. Early Weed Prevention Is Everything</h3><p>Here\'s a truth most homeowners learn the hard way: <strong>weed prevention is 10x more effective than weed removal.</strong> Pre-emergent herbicide needs to go down before soil temps hit 55\u00b0F consistently \u2014 that\'s usually late March to early April in Madison. Miss that window and you\'re fighting crabgrass, dandelions, and clover all summer.</p>',
    spotlight: { show: false },
