    intro_text: 'April in Madison means the growing season is officially ON, {{first_name}}. Your grass is pushing new growth, weeds are germinating, and every decision you make this month ripples through the entire summer. Here\'s how to get it right from the start.',
    content_html: '<h3>1. Mowing Height: 3-3.5 Inches \u2014 No Exceptions</h3><p>This is the single most impactful thing you can do for your lawn. <strong>Set your mower to 3-3.5 inches and leave it there.</strong> Taller grass shades the soil (which prevents weed seeds from germinating), retains moisture longer (less watering), and develops deeper roots (better drought resistance).</p><h3>2. Watering Schedule: Start Smart</h3><p>April in Wisconsin usually provides enough rain that you don\'t need supplemental watering. But if we hit a dry stretch (7+ days without rain), water <strong>early morning (6-9am), twice per week, for 30-45 minutes per zone.</strong> Morning watering lets blades dry before evening, which prevents fungal disease.</p><h3>3. When to Apply Herbicide</h3><p>If you didn\'t get pre-emergent down in late March, there\'s still a window in early April \u2014 but it\'s closing fast. Soil temperatures are climbing, and once they hit 55\u00b0F consistently, crabgrass starts germinating. Our herbicide program uses professional-grade products applied at exactly the right time.</p>',
