    content_html: '<h3>1. Deep Watering vs. Frequent Watering</h3><p>This is the hill we will die on: <strong>water deeply and infrequently.</strong> Two to three times per week, 30-45 minutes per zone, early morning. Daily light watering trains grass roots to stay shallow. Deep watering pushes roots down 4-6 inches. <strong>Total weekly target: 1-1.5 inches of water.</strong></p><h3>2. Heat Stress Signs to Watch For</h3><p><strong>Footprinting:</strong> Walk across your lawn \u2014 if the grass doesn\'t spring back, it needs water. <strong>Blue-gray color:</strong> The lawn is conserving moisture. <strong>Wilting blades:</strong> Grass folding lengthwise is desperate for water. A good deep soak brings it back within 24-48 hours.</p><h3>3. Mowing in the Heat</h3><p>During hot spells (90\u00b0F+), <strong>raise your mowing height by half an inch</strong> to 3.5-4 inches. The extra leaf blade shades the soil, reducing evaporation and keeping root zones cooler. Never mow during the heat of the day.</p>',
